{{Cleanup|date=April 2010}} {{Refimprove|date=March 2012}} {{WPMIXInfobox | iba = yes | sourcelink = pina | name = Piña Colada | image = Piña Colada.jpg | caption = | type = cocktail | flaming = | rum = yes | served = blended | garnish = [[pineapple]] slice and [[maraschino cherry]] | drinkware = poco | ingredients = *30 ml (one part) [[Light rum|white rum]] *30 ml (one part) [[cream of coconut]] *90 ml (3 parts) [[pineapple juice]] | prep = Mix with crushed ice until smooth. Pour into chilled glass, garnish and serve. | notes = | footnotes = }} The '''piña colada''' (Spanish: ''piña'', pineapple + ''colada'', strained) is a sweet, [[rum]]-based [[cocktail]] made with rum, [[cream of coconut]], and [[pineapple juice]], usually served either blended or shaken with ice. It may be garnished with a pineapple wedge, a [[maraschino cherry]] or both. The piña colada has been the official beverage of [[Puerto Rico]] since 1978.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://hotels.about.com/b/a/104906.htm| title=Celebrate Two of Mankind's Greatest Inventions| accessdate=2007-06-19}}</ref>
==Origin== On August 16, 1954 at the [[Caribe Hilton Hotel|Caribe Hilton]]'s Beachcomber Bar in San Juan, Puerto Rico by its alleged creator, Ramón "Monchito" Marrero. Apparently, the hotel management had requested Monchito to mix a signature drink; after three months of experimenting the first piña colada was born.
==Popularity== This cocktail has been famous in Puerto Rico since 1978, and it became more widely known after [[Rupert Holmes]] released his song "[[Escape (Rupert Holmes song)|Escape]]", commonly known as "The Piña Colada Song". <!-- It was also Del Boy's favourite drink in Only Fools And Horses -->
==Preparation== There are many recipes of how to make a piña colada but the one that his friends tell in the book of José L. Díaz De Villegas to be the original recipe created by Monchito, is the following: Pour 3 ounces of coconut cream, 6 ounces of pineapple juice and 1{{fraction|1|2}} ounces of white rum into a [[blender]] or shaker with crushed ice, and blend or shake very well until smooth. Pour into chilled glass, garnish with pineapple wedge and/or a maraschino cherry.
==Variations== * Different proportions may be used. For example, 1 part rum, 2 each of pineapple juice and coconut cream. * Dark rum may be used. * Amaretto colada — [[amaretto]] substituted for rum<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bartender.com/2calendar/cal-2003/cal-0603.htm| title=Frozen/Mixed — Amaretto Colada| accessdate=2007-06-20}}</ref> * Lava Flow — strawberry [[daiquiri]] and piña colada blended together<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gohawaii.about.com/od/drinks/r/lava_flow.htm| title=Lava Flow| accessdate=2007-06-20}}</ref> * [[Staten Island Ferry (cocktail)|Staten Island Ferry]] — coconut rum and pineapple juice over ice * Virgin piña colada or piñita colada — without the rum
==See also== {{Portal|Puerto Rico}} * [[Coco López]] * "[[Escape (Rupert Holmes song)|Escape]]" - also known as "The Piña Colada Song" * [[Ramón López Irizarry]] {{Commons category}}
